		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64552855">For starters I would recommend<nobr> <wbr></nobr>.deb based systems because upgrades and installations are generally easy.<br>
Go for a KDE desktop as they are not that different to Windows but can be configured any way you fancy.<br>
As a distribution I would suggest Neon, Kubuntu or Mint.<br> <br>
About hardware, stick with some brands like Fedora, Dell, Asus and Acer.<br>
As others said, use the (USB) Live function to check various distro's and first install as a dual boot next to Windows.<br>
Printers are best checked through one of the several sites listing Linux compatibility but Brother and Xerox usually work.<br>
Scanners work a lot better than used to be, if not, use Vuescan and (for a price) nearly all are working, even when the manufacturer is no longer supporting a model.<br>
LibreOffice is the office suit of choice.<br>
For photo's I like Gwenview and for simple edits Showfoto, the Gimp and Krita can do more complicated operations.<br>
A good video editor is Kdenlive.</div>
	</div>

